t, Anglesey, Wales":"Llantrisant, Anglesey, Wales","Llantrisant, Anglesey, Wales":"Llantrisant, Anglesey, Wales","Anglesey, Wales":"Anglesey, Wales"},"en":{"about 1455–":"about 1455–Deceased","1455–Male":"1455–Deceased","1456–Male":"1456–Deceased","1452–Female":"1452–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1470–Female":"1470–Deceased","1485–1560":"1485–1560","1490–Female":"1490–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1440–1538":"1440–1538","1418–Female":"1418–Deceased","about 1470":"about 1470","about 1490":"about 1490","1440":"1440","1560":"1560","1470":"1470","1490":"1490","1469":"1469","1456":"1456","1455":"1455","1485":"1485","1452":"1452","about 1455":"about 1455","1418":"1418","1538":"1538","of Y Chwaen,Llantrisaint,Anglesey,Wales":"Llantrisant, Anglesey, Wales","Prysaeddfed,Bodedern,Anglesey,Wales":"Bodedern, Anglesey, Wales, United Kingdom","of Y Chwaen, Llantrisaint, Anglesey, Wales":"Llantrisant, Anglesey, Wales","Llantrisant, Anglesey, Wales":"Llantrisant, Anglesey, Wales","Anglesey, Wales":"Anglesey, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"ap","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: variant of   Abt  .","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): habitational name from Apt, the Yiddish name of Opatów in Świętokrzyskie Voivodeship, Poland. The placename (in German, Yiddish, and Polish) is from a root meaning ‘abbot’, the place having been named for the local abbey. Compare   Abt  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Abt","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Helmut, Horst, Johann, Kurt.","German and Dutch: from Middle Low German or Middle Dutch <i>abt</i> ‘abbot’, hence a metonymic occupational name for a servant of an abbot or a nickname for someone thought to resemble an abbot in some way. In some instances it may have been a topographic or habitational name referring to a house named with this word.","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): variant of   Abt  , a habitational name from Opatów in Poland."]},{"name":"Apter","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Avrohom, Bronya, Eliezer, Naftali.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): habitational name for someone from Apt (see   Apt  ).","English: habitational name from Aptor in Marldon, Devon, composed of Old English <i>uppe</i> ‘up, above’ + <i>torr</i> ‘rocky outcrop’."]}]},{"name":"Llywelyn","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Welsh: variant of   Llewellyn  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Llewellyn","meanings":["Welsh: from the personal name <i>Llywelyn</i>, derived from British Celtic <i>Lugubelinos</i>, itself from the divine name <i>Lugus</i> + an uncertain second element often used alone as a name. Through association with <i>llew</i> ‘lion’, it was altered to <i>Llewelyn</i>. This was the name of two princes of north Wales who held the Normans at bay for many years in the 13th century. Etymologically speaking, the form with a fourth <i>-l-</i> is an error, not found as an original Welsh name, but this is now much the most common spelling in the US."]}]},{"name":"Gruffudd","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Old Welsh <i>Grip(p)iud</i>, from an unexplained first element + a second element meaning ‘lord, prince’.  Gruffydd ap Llewelyn  (  d. 1063 ) was one of the most able rulers of Wales in the Middle Ages, scoring notable victories over the English until he was eventually defeated by  King Harold  in  1063 ."],"variants":[{"name":"Griffudd","meanings":["From Old Welsh <i>Grip(p)iud</i>, from an unexplained first element + a second element meaning ‘lord, prince’.  Gruffydd ap Llewelyn  (  d. 1063 ) was one of the most able rulers of Wales in the Middle Ages, scoring notable victories over the English until he was eventually defeated by  King Harold  in  1063 ."]},{"name":"Gruffud","meanings":["From Old Welsh <i>Grip(p)iud</i>, from an unexplained first element + a second element meaning ‘lord, prince’.  Gruffydd ap Llewelyn  (  d. 1063 ) was one of the most able rulers of Wales in the Middle Ages, scoring notable victories over the English until he was eventually defeated by  King Harold  in  1063 ."]},{"name":"Griffith","meanings":["Anglicized form of   Gruffudd ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Gruffudd ap Llywelyn was born about 1455, in Llantrisant, Anglesey, Wales, his father, Meurig ap Llewelyn, was 17 and his mother, Miss ferch Jenkin, was 39. He had at least 4 daughters with Catrin ferch John."},"et":{"about 1455–":"umbes 1455–Surnud","1455–Male":"1455–Surnud","1456–Male":"1456–Surnud","1452–Female":"1452–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1470–Female":"1470–Surnud","1485–1560":"1485–1560","1490–Female":"1490–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1440–1538":"1440–1538","1418–Female":"1418–Surnud","about 1470":"umbes 1470","about 1490":"umbes 1490","1440":"1440","1560":"1560","1470":"1470","1490":"1490","1469":"1469","1456":"1456","1455":"1455","1485":"1485","1452":"1452","about 1455":"umbes 1455","1418":"1418","1538":"1538","of Y Chwaen,Llantrisaint,Anglesey,Wales":"Llantrisant, Anglesey, Wales","Prysaeddfed,Bodedern,Anglesey,Wales":"Bodedern, Anglesey, Wales, United Kingdom","of Y Chwaen, Llantrisaint, Anglesey, Wales":"Llantrisant, Anglesey, Wales","Llantrisant, Anglesey, Wales":"Llantrisant, Anglesey, Wales","Anglesey, Wales":"Anglesey, Wales"},"fi":{"about 1455–":"noin 1455–Kuollut","1455–Male":"1455–Kuollut","1456–Male":"1456–Kuollut","1452–Female":"1452–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1470–Female":"1470–Kuollut","1485–1560":"1485–1560","1490–Female":"1490–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1440–1538":"1440–1538","1418–Female":"1418–Kuollut","about 1470":"noin 1470","about 1490":"noin 1490","1440":"1440","1560":"1560","1470":"1470","1490":"1490","1469":"1469","1456":"1456","1455":"1455","1485":"1485","1452":"1452","about 1455":"noin 1455","1418":"1418","1538":"1538","of Y Chwaen,Llantrisaint,Anglesey,Wales":"Llantrisant, Anglesey, Wales","Prysaeddfed,Bodedern,Angl